    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>New Orleans</placeName>
                <date>Oct 14 1849</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Isaac Leeser Esq</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Revd &amp; Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Yours of the <date>27</date> Ult. I duly recd &amp;<lb/> regret my
                not being enabled to answer<lb/> sooner &amp; even now I am <sic>Compeld</sic>
                to<lb/> write in haste having to attend a<lb/> Bris this morning. My Letter of the<lb/>
                <date>14th Sept</date> was before you</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Regarding the <persName>Revd H A Henry</persName><lb/> I have read
                attentively all you say<lb/> of that Gentleman and altho I would<lb/> prefer
                    <sic>defering</sic> to enter into any Immediate<lb/> Correspondence with the
                Revd Gentleman<lb/> as this moment still I should very<lb/> much like to learn his
                popularity, exact<lb/> capacity &amp; what salary He would require<lb/> I notice
                your having Inserted in this<lb/> month Occident my Advertisement it<lb/> is well
                &amp; as we are now open to all <sic>aplicants</sic><lb/> would it not be as well to
                wait &amp; see who<lb/> may desire the office perhaps the Gentleman<lb/> himself may
                think proper to address me<lb/> altho I fully agree with you<del>rself</del>
                that<lb/> $1.000 is but a small salary for a<lb/> capable minister to live
                respectable<lb/> with. On next <date>Sunday</date> I shall hold the</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>Election for officers to serve the ensuing year<lb/> like many other Congregations we
                have many<lb/> members who pay but little attention to their<lb/> religion or who
                evince less Interest in the<lb/> affairs of the Congregation For many years<lb/> I
                have served in various capacities and<lb/> although from a few <add>?</add> now
                Number<lb/> nearly 200 members still the same<lb/> apathy exists now particularly on
                the part of<lb/> those Engaged in extensive Commerce. I<lb/> have generally found
                the whole Burden of<lb/> the affairs of the Congregation devol<add>?</add> on<lb/>
                myself I am very sensitive of want of<lb/> Energy on the part of those who I
                consider should<lb/> take that Interest required the whole Burden falling on me is
                too much for my weak Con<lb/>-stitution justice to myself &amp; family Compels<lb/>
                me against the wishes of our members to<lb/> accept no office at least for the
                present.<lb/> Who they will Elect I know not Vanity aside<lb/> they have not one
                amongst them that will<lb/> work &amp; use his every Endeavour as I have<lb/> done
                to promote an Interest in our<lb/> Holy Religion &amp; to raise them in the
                Estimation of our Community In<lb/> this hasty scrawl I cannot attempt<lb/> to say
                half what I could wish but what<lb/> I wish to convey to you is this: I should<lb/>
                prefer no action in opening correspondence</p>
            <p rend="The following number is written at the bottom of the page."
                    ><date>10-14-1849</date>E</p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p>with any minister until after the Election<lb/> when that is past P. S. I will
                address<lb/> you again. You can form no Idea of the<lb/> duties of a Parnass in the
                City one half of<lb/> my time is occupied with the Service of the Congregation<lb/>
                I have now a list out for signatures<lb/> to close our stores on <add>Hebrew</add>
                If I succeed I<lb/> shall Indeed be happy I am sorry to say<lb/> hardly an
                    <sic>Isrealite</sic>
                <add>Heb</add> keep their <date>Sabbath</date> what<lb/> a field for Comment is this
                on the part of the<lb/> other denominations. after the Election I shall<lb/> have
                more leisure (being determined not to<lb/> accept <sic>offise</sic> again) &amp;
                then I will address<lb/> you more at length</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">The ship Milan is in port &amp; tomorrow no<lb/> doubt I shall be in
                receipt of your<lb/> Books &amp; will Cr<add>?</add> you accordingly<lb/> Many of
                the <sic>Pourtigesee</sic> members &amp; also<lb/>
                <persName>DeSilva</persName> find fault with your Books. “Too lean”<lb/>
                <add>says one</add> “not correct &amp;c,” <add>says another</add> &amp; yet they
                have no<lb/>
                <sic>Preyer</sic> Books amongst them. Its strange.<lb/> If none were here on sale
                all would want<lb/> Here they are cheaper than they could send for<lb/> them none
                will Buy.</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Wishing you Long Life</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Happiness &amp; Prosperity</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">I have the Honor to</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Subscribe myself your Obt Svt</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <persName role="author">Isaac Hart</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
